<div id="review_94016988" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/94016988" />
    <a title="Hans" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1142366-hans"><img alt="Hans" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1292037372p2/1142366.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/94016988?book_show_action=true">Mar 14, 2010</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Hans" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Hans" href="/user/show/1142366-hans">Hans</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Mass Market Paperback 9782253098287" href="/book/show/454438.Zadig_et_autres_contes">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1142366-hans?shelf=philosophy">philosophy</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1142366-hans?shelf=psychology">psychology</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1142366-hans?shelf=french-literature">french-literature</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer94016988" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13582916793340652586">Zadig is like Candide without the naive optimism. A tale of ones man&apos;s plunge from the heights of good fortune to the depths of misery to being back on top. The core struggle is the internal one Zadig faces over first understanding his fate and then accepting it.<br/><br/>What made it enjoyable for me was the cocept of how fortune and misfortune is nothing more than perception. Blessings can be curses and curses can be blessing. What seems like a string of bad luck can in fact turn out to be more capable </span>
  <span id="freeText13582916793340652586" style="display:none">Zadig is like Candide without the naive optimism. A tale of ones man's plunge from the heights of good fortune to the depths of misery to being back on top. The core struggle is the internal one Zadig faces over first understanding his fate and then accepting it.<br /><br />What made it enjoyable for me was the cocept of how fortune and misfortune is nothing more than perception. Blessings can be curses and curses can be blessing. What seems like a string of bad luck can in fact turn out to be more capable of teaching more valuable lessons than good luck. <br /><br />My favorite character was the crazy hermit whose actions appear mad but were in fact very calculated. This stuns Zadig until he sees the wisdom behind it and then realizes he has been in communion with the divine.<br /><br />I am not entirely sure what Voltaire was getting at with this story. He obviously wrote "Candide" as a criticism of the over-optimism of the time when he lived, and yet you could say this was an optimistic story.<br />It is a similar tale along the lines of Joseph and his brothers from the Old Testament, as well as the story of Job. Even though the ending may feel a bit too over the top, I did enjoy several parts of the book.<br /><br /><br /><br />A few fun quotes so far:<br /><br />"The Glances of her Eye, which she would turn away,<br />if perceiv'd, and which she fix'd upon his, kindled in the Heart of<br />_Zadig_ a Fire, which struck him with Amazement. He did all he could<br />to smother it; he call'd up all the Philosophy he was Master of to<br />his Aid; but all in vain, for no Consolation arose from those<br />Reflections". <br /><br /> I enjoyed this passage because of the idea of using philosophy to fight one's burning love for another. I have heard that before that some use philosophy to smother their feelings.<br /><br /><br />"and when, against his Inclination, they (his eyes) met with those of the Queen, he found, that tho' drown'd in Tears, they darted Flames of Fire: They seem'd in Silence to intimate, that they were afraid of being in love with each other; and that both burn'd with a Fire which both condemn'd". <br /><br />Desire always burns hotter when it is forbidden, one of the strange contradictions of being human.</span>
  <a data-text-id="13582916793340652586" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


