<div id="review_2598133386" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2598133386" />
    <a title="Bruce" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/12242873-bruce"><img alt="Bruce" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1587906182p2/12242873.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2598133386?book_show_action=true">Feb 05, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Bruce" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Bruce" href="/user/show/12242873-bruce">Bruce</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780554817545" href="/book/show/7315810-zadig-and-other-stories">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2598133386" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6677293061400500237"> We have no Voltaire. There is no one. He was a philosopher, and we have no philosophers. We have pundits, meretricious martinets, fame seekers , and self-aggrandizers. <br/> This book, &quot; Voltaire, Candide, Zadig, and selected stories&quot;, is not one book. There is no &quot;one story&quot;. Voltaire was born in 1694, and early on, in the court circles. His satire and lampoons were so startling that he was imprisoned in The Bastille twice. <br/> Voltaire lived during the &quot; Age of Enlightenment&quot;. It was so enlightening </span>
  <span id="freeText6677293061400500237" style="display:none"> We have no Voltaire. There is no one. He was a philosopher, and we have no philosophers. We have pundits, meretricious martinets, fame seekers , and self-aggrandizers. <br /> This book, " Voltaire, Candide, Zadig, and selected stories", is not one book. There is no "one story". Voltaire was born in 1694, and early on, in the court circles. His satire and lampoons were so startling that he was imprisoned in The Bastille twice. <br /> Voltaire lived during the " Age of Enlightenment". It was so enlightening that his criticism and barbs forced him into exile in England for four years ( the antimony of our current modus operandi, where we indict, slander, slam and have special investigations ad nauseum). Upon returning, it didn't take him long to be chastised once again, his " Lettres philosophiques sur les Anglais" , an attack on the French church and state caused, him, about the age of 40, to flee into exile again. For 20 years, he lived away from France. <br /> The lengthiest stories, " Candide" and " Zadig", are loaded c the torments of the time-the auto-da-fe, relegation to rowing in the galley, running the gantlet among the Bulgarians, rape, having half a buttock cut of amongst others.. <br /> Three shorter stories were most interesting- " The World As It Is", " Micromegas" and " Story of A Good Brahman". excerpt: " The archimandrite admitted to him that he got a hundred thousand crowns of income for having taken a vow of poverty, and that he exercised a rather extensive rule by virtue of his humility...".... " he asked a few men of letters to dinner..they praised two sorts of persons, the dead and themselves, and never their contemporaries. One of them besought( another) in a low voice to exterminate an author who had not praised him enough five years before".<br /> "Story of a Good Brahman" excerpt- " I have been studying for forty years wasted; I teach others and I know nothing; this situation brings into my soul so much humiliation and disgust that life is unbearable to me. ....I retreat to my house overwhelmed with my curiosity and my ignorance. I read our ancient books, and they redouble the darkness I am in.... I am sometimes ready to fall into despair, when I think that after all my seeking I know neither where I come from, nor what I am, nor where I shall go, nor what shall become of me."<br /> Voltaire died in Paris in 1778, two years after our country began. I wonder if the Founding Fathers ever met him, and had any conversations with him, because he was the true enlightenment.</span>
  <a data-text-id="6677293061400500237" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

