<div id="review_4016249810" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4016249810" />
    <a title="Tara Parsons" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/135420769-tara-parsons"><img alt="Tara Parsons" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1621812911p2/135420769.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4016249810?book_show_action=true">May 26, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Tara Parsons" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Tara Parsons" href="/user/show/135420769-tara-parsons">Tara Parsons</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4016249810" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12909168916395673505">It was mediocre— although better than anything by Ayn Rand. <br/><br/>My main qualm with the novella is that the eponymous protagonist was flat. I know it was purposeful; nonetheless, I despise when authors believe they must sacrifice character depth in order to better illustrate their message. I find such a technique to do the antitheses, as the lack of character depth makes it hard for readers to empathize with the situation and consequently comprehend the theme— in reference to Kant’s view that art is </span>
  <span id="freeText12909168916395673505" style="display:none">It was mediocre— although better than anything by Ayn Rand. <br /><br />My main qualm with the novella is that the eponymous protagonist was flat. I know it was purposeful; nonetheless, I despise when authors believe they must sacrifice character depth in order to better illustrate their message. I find such a technique to do the antitheses, as the lack of character depth makes it hard for readers to empathize with the situation and consequently comprehend the theme— in reference to Kant’s view that art is the best philosophical medium à cause de its ability to make the reader empathize. <br /><br />Despite the plot being adequate, I hate the happy ending— being spoiled by beautiful, luscious Hemingway zero endings. Plus, I find Voltaire's message to be too optimistic. </span>
  <a data-text-id="12909168916395673505" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


